Tension heightened in Enugu following a bloody clash at Emene,  involving members of the Indigenous Peoples of Biafra (IPOB) and security agents. Although the number of casualties has not been officially confirmed as
at the time filling this report, unconfirmed sources said many were
feared dead during the bloody clash that took place yesterday. It was gathered that trouble started at about 7.00am when some police
personnel stormed an IPOB gathering at Community Secondary School,
Emene and attempted to disperse the group and make arrests. The IPOB had been proscribed by the Federal Government. The IPOB members were reportedly holding their usual meeting when the
security operatives swooped in on them, but the encounter was said to
have turned bloody when the Biafra campaigners resisted arrest and
overpowered the security agents In order to contain the situation, a reinforcement of security agents
comprising the police, DSS and army arrived the place in several
patrol vans in the midst of the confusion, began to shoot sporadically
targeting the fleeing pro-Biafra campaigners. Sounds of gunfire and teargas fumes filled the axis between St Patrick
Secondary School and St Joseph Catholic Church along the old Abakaliki
Road. Some residents, who were on their way to 7.00am mass scampered for
safety while those already in the Church had to endure tear gas fumes,
that enveloped the entire environment. As at the time of filling this report, Emene was still tensed security
agents flooded the area, restricting movement of persons and vehicles
as they searched for IPOB members. Both the Enugu State Police command and the IPOB leadership had yet to
speak on the clash.